commit.message: Remove pre-1.0 history entries from package description
Minor fixes to version-history.rst

Remove status images from release’s description

Presumably, if a release is made, the code and its documentation builds
correctly.  As such, including status images from Read the Docs and
Travis doesn’t add any value to the package description.

Change `setup.py` to strip those when generating the description from
`README.rst` file.

Fix setup.py’s CommandMixin.copy_file using ancient method signature

The CommandMixin.copy_file in the setup.py file used an ancient
signature from the times of Python 2.x I believe.  This resulted in

    TypeError: copy_file() got an unexpected keyword argument 'verbose'
    TypeError: copy_file() got an unexpected keyword argument 'dry_run'

exceptiens when trying to build a new release.  Use new signature
which no longer has `verbose` and `dry_run` arguments.

Make children argument of the node_factory convertible to bool

As the moment, the `children` argument passed to the `node_factory`
callback of the `Trie.traverse` method is a generator.  This means
that to determine whether node has any children, the factory has to at
least attempt to generate the first child.

Change the `children` argument into an iterator with a `__bool__`
method.  It thus makes it possible to determine whether node has
children in constant time without having to iterate over them.

Fixes: https://github.com/mina86/pygtrie/pull/2

Remove ‘upgrading from 0.9.x’ and other small documentation improvements

It’s been a while since the 1.0 release and by now there should be no
one who remembers the 0.9.x times.  As such, documentation of how to
upgrade from 0.9.x should no longer be necessary and can be safely
removed.

While doing that, expand a little on installation instruction.  Among
other things, remove mention of copying the `pygtrie.py` file manually.
Since the `__version__` is now populated during installation, it’s no
longer the same effect to just use tha file directly.  Anyone who wants
to do it anyway is on their own but will probably figure it out without
documentation so there’s no point advertising this unsupported method.

Lastly, fix some other minor wording issues and typos.
Use ‘-X dev’ flag when running tests

Remove Python 2.6 classifier

It’s been ten years since Python 2.7 was released and pygtrie has
not been tested with Python 2.6 for quite a while.  Remove Python
2.6 from the package classifiers list to avoid any confusion in
case the library doesn’t work with that version of the language.
This shouldn’t affect anyone.

While at it, mention pygtrie is Python 2.x and Python 3.x compatible
in the documentation.

Slight rework of value popping code

Slight negative delta, _cleanup_trace and _pop_from_node replaced with
a single _pop_value method and pick_child method of children collection
classes removed.  I call that a good change…

Make setup.py fill in __version__ automatically

Instead of me having to manually update the __version__ on each release,
change setup.py such that it will do it for me whenever new release is
prepared (i.e. inside of the sdist command) or during installation.

Prepare 2.3.3 release with iterating over trie with sorting enabled fix

Most notably, this release fixes AttributeError when trying to iterate
over a trie which has sorting enabled.
Small documentation improvements

Turn ‘builddoc’ into proper setuptools command

Instead of a hacky way of handling ‘builddoc’ sub-command when running
setup.py, make ‘build_doc’ into a proper setup sub-command (including
--dry-run support).

Fix iteration when sorting is enabled

Define ‘sorted_items’ on a ‘_NoChildren’ class since that method is
used when iterating over nodes.  Without this defined, trying to
traverse a trie with sorting enabled results in an exception:

    AttributeError: '_NoChildren' object has no attribute 'sorted_items'

Fixes: https://github.com/google/pygtrie/pull/31
Reported-by: Pallab Pain <pallabkumarpain@gmail.com>
Fix _OneChild __slots__ typo

Add setter to _Step.value

Make step’s ‘value’ property settable in addition to being readable at the
moment.  This introduces a much more familiar interfaces and deprecates
the set method.

Prepare 2.3.2 release with a trivial metadata fix

Fix generation of long_description from RST files.  The old code in
setup.py would put ‘class’ and ‘func’ keywords in long description
rather than names of the classes and functions.
Prepare 2.3.1 release with fixes to PrefixSet.__init__ and copying
Improve ‘version-history.rst’ by adding hyperlinks to classes and methods
Speed up unit tests

Add support for copy module

In addition to providing ‘copy’ method on Trie and PrefixSet objects,
add support for the ‘copy’ module.

Before, ‘copy.copy’ would return a new trie (or prefix set) which shared
the node structure with the old object. ‘copy.deepcopy’ worked correctly
but this commit makes the implementation more efficient.
Small docstring improvements
Optimise PrefixSet.add method

Fix prefixes not pruning long keys in PrefixSet.__init__

When adding values from an iterable passed to PrefixSet._-init__,
the method did not prevent long keys from being inserted when
their prefix was already present in the set.  This caused spurious
elements in the set.

Reported-by: Tal Maimon <tal161195@gmail.com>
Fixes: https://github.com/google/pygtrie/issues/29
Trivial documentation improvements

µbenchmark suggest cPython prefers ‘def foo’ to ‘foo = lambda’ so use it

µbenchmarks suggest that cPython prefers methods defined with ‘def foo’
to those using ‘foo = lambda’.  Furthermore, static methods are slower
than non-static.

Furthermore, using ‘def foo’ rather than ‘foo = lambda’ helps pylint
analyse the code such that it can detect more potential issues.

Based on all that, don’t use staticmethod just to avoid ‘no-self-use’
warning (instead, disable that warning) and don’t use ‘foo = lambda’
syntax (even though it’s more concise).

Drop _basestring global in favour of inlining base string type detection

_basestring is used in StringTrie.__init__.  Instead of using a global
variable inline detecting the base string type in the __init__ method.
Also make it more concise.
Fix lint warnings in test.py introduced by previous commit
Make sure copy() preserves sorting flag

Reduce memory footprint of single-child nodes

On 64-bit CPython implementation size of one-element dict (as
reported by sys.getsizeof) is 240 bytes which seem a bit wasteful.
Use a separate representation for one-element mappings, one which
takes only 56 bytes.
